result.execSummary:
Giorgio Armani Davis was extradited to another county, state or jurisdiction. Extradition means Giorgio Armani Davis was accused or convicted of an offense in another county, state or jurisdiction and was taken there to face their charge(s) or conviction.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: copy letter and waiver sent to Governer

Clerk: Shelly:
Defendant Giorgio Armani Davis in court with attorney Sean Drury. Defendant Giorgio Armani Davis in custody. David R. Knaapen appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

11:11 a.m.  Court calls case.
Set for extradition hearing today.
Atty Knaapen states that he has been in contact with the extradition office in Minnesota.
Atty Knaapen states the the defendant intends to waive extradition.
Atty Drury states on the record that his client will be waiving extradition.
Court questions the defendant and is waiver of the extradition hearing to Minnesota.
Court questions defendant if he has had enough time to speak with his Attorney regarding the extradition hearing.
Defendant is freely, knowingly and voluntarily waiving his right to extradition.

BY THE COURT:
Court is waiting on the Order and this needs to be signed in the presence of the Judge.


11:55 a.m.  Court recalls case and states appearances.
Defendant signs the extradition paperwork in front of Judge.
Court signs orders as of today's date.
State Public Defender - Order Appointing Counsel - Atty Drury

Minnesota case 62-CR-10-563
- Recommendaiton of the Probatio Officer and Order Vacating Stay of Imposition of Sentence
 - Order Vacating Stay of Impostion Sentence

4:20 PM Court calls case.
Atty Knaapen states appearances.
This matter is brought on the calendar for the purposes of an extradition hearing.
Giorgio Davis appears in person, in the custody of the jail.

Atty Knaapen addresses the Court, has a copy of a warrant from the Court in Ramsey County, Minnesota.
Case number is 62CR-10-563

The warrant was to apprehension of the Defendant. Defendant committed the felony theft crime on July 13, 2010. Sentence was an imposed and stayed sentence with probation for 5 years. Probation and parole requested a warrant  because Defendant failed to report.  Probation requested a warrant on September 10, 2013 and the Court in Minnesota granted it on September 16, 2013.

Defendant was taken into custody yesterday.

Court is to determine if this Defendant is the person that is on the paperwork.
Defendant indicates that he is the person in question, his date of birth is September 19, 1991.

This Court has been presented by a warrant dated September 16, 2013 from Ramsey County, Minnesota.

Court informs Defendant of right to counsel, public defender's office.
Defendant states he has not been seen by anyone from the public defender's office.

Atty Knaapen does not have the paperwork from Minnesota.
Defendant is going to be challenging the extradition back to Minnesota.
An extradition hearing will need to be set.

Defendant addresses the Court, 2117 Wyatt is the address where Defendant has been living at.
Defendant works at Rockman's Catering. Defendant lives with his brother.

State recommends bond of $25,000 cash.

BY THE COURT:
Court will order a $5,000 cash bond
